[3] North Carolina
Date: 18 Dec 2009
Source: DigTriad.com [edited]
<http://www.digtriad.com/includes/tools/print.aspx?storyid=134645>


8th case of rabies reported in Davidson County
----------------------------------------------
The Davidson County Health Department reports a new case of rabies,
bringing the total to 8 for the year. On 17 Dec 2009, a dog was in a fight
with a rabid raccoon in Lexington, North Carolina. The dog was not properly
vaccinated and had to be killed, according to animal control. No humans
were exposed.

Animal Control says not to handle your animal with bare hands after it has
had contact with a wild animal. Saliva from the wild animal may still be
present on the domestic animal's fur and, by handling the animal, you may
expose yourself to the rabies virus.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[It is fortunate there was no human being exposed in any of these
situations. It is unfortunate a couple of dogs lost their lives, primarily
because they were not vaccinated. Rabies vaccination is a very cheap
insurance against a very deadly disease for you and your pets.

Rabies is caused by the rabies virus, of the genus Lyssavirus and family
Rhabdoviridae. The bullet-shaped RNA virus has 3 major components: surface
glycoprotein (G protein), outer envelope protein (M or matrix protein), and
nucleocapsid. Rabies virus is transmitted by bite or saliva of an infected
mammal. Any mammal can carry and potentially transmit the virus, but
carnivorous species and bats are usually the agents of transmission

None of these reports identifies the stain, although it is probably the
raccoon rabies in these cases. 5 antigenic variants of rabies strains are
recognized in the United States. The single raccoon strain is the
predominant strain.

Portions of this comment have been extracted from
<http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/968262-overview> - Mod.TG]
